<seg id="1">Joint report on the parallel audits of expenditure on the construction of the Prague- Dresden motorway Preliminary remark Modern, united Europe could only cope with the high volume of traffic between the partner states without trans-European motorways with significant restrictions and quality losses.</seg>
<seg id="2">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFBlank</seg>
<seg id="3">High-quality transport networks are essential for maintaining and raising living standards in Europe.</seg>
<seg id="4">Ensuring fast, safe, reliable and economic passenger and freight transport is an important task for the state.</seg>
<seg id="5">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFBlank</seg>
<seg id="6">It requires a high level of organisational, technical and financial efforts.</seg>
<seg id="7">When building and developing a sustainable European transport infrastructure, difficult compromises often have to be made with European and national policy objectives, such as the preservation of the environment.</seg>
<seg id="8">It is precisely because of the necessary environmental protection measures that the construction of the transport infrastructure is expensive.</seg>
<seg id="9">When planning and awarding the construction of transport routes, administrations can save considerable financial resources and use them for other useful purposes through careful action and decision-making.</seg>
<seg id="10">One of the tasks of state audit authorities is to identify deficiencies that prevent optimum economy, efficiency and effectiveness in expenditure on the construction of transport facilities.</seg>
<seg id="11">The audit authorities should not only draw the attention of the administrations to the shortcomings identified, but also to propose improvements for the benefit of the citizens and for the benefit of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="12">Summary</seg>
<seg id="13">In 2005 and 2006, the two Supreme Audit Institutions of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic, the Federal Audit Office (BRH) and the Nejvy's Kontroln'ad (Nk) carried out parallel audits of the expenditure for the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway (Motorway D 8 in the Czech Republic and Motorway A 17 in the Federal Republic of Germany).</seg>
<seg id="14">The two motorways are connected by a border bridge jointly financed by both states.</seg>
<seg id="15">The cooperation with the NA enabled the BRH to carry out an in-depth examination of the cost-effectiveness of the use of funds in the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="16">In the course of the cooperation with the BRH, the NKA received data from German bridges and tunnels for its own cost comparisons.</seg>
<seg id="17">In 2000, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany signed a contract for the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="18">In line with the progress of the planning, the date of completion was finally set for the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">However, during the procurement procedure, the Road and Highways Directorate of the Czech Republic (RMD) made errors which delayed the procedure and shortened the available construction time.</seg>
<seg id="20">The contract with the contractor was therefore concluded later than planned.</seg>
<seg id="21">The contractor promised the accelerated construction of the bridge by the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="22">However, the RMD had to accept considerable additional costs.</seg>
<seg id="23">As part of the joint audit work, the prices of motorway bridges on the D8 and A 17 were compared. The benchmark for the price comparison of the bridges was the size of the bridge area.</seg>
<seg id="24">A price analysis using statistical methods identified bridges with high costs per square meter.</seg>
<seg id="25">The analysis showed that the border bridge was the most expensive among the large bridges with lengths of more than 100 m.</seg>
<seg id="26">This was also due to the increase in prices as a result of the delays in the awarding of contracts.</seg>
<seg id="27">The comparison of the prices of the tunnel works showed that the prices of the tunnels in the course of the D 8 are considerably higher than the prices of comparable tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="28">In future audits of the economic viability of transport infrastructure expenditure, both BRH and NKO can rely on a data collection of bridge and tunnel prices.</seg>
<seg id="29">Both courts recommend standardizing bridge constructions and performing steel composite and special constructions only where prestressed concrete constructions are inappropriate.</seg>
<seg id="30">The course of the examination was characterized by teamwork and an open approach.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the parallel audit, the auditors from both sides exchanged their expertise and skills.</seg>
<seg id="32">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="33">This report deals with parallel audits of expenditure on the construction of the motorway from Dresden to Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="34">The focus of the audit was on economy, cost-effectiveness and effectiveness of the use of funds.</seg>
<seg id="35">The parallel audits were carried out by the BRH in Germany and the NA in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="36">in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="37">The NA, the NKA examined the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of expenditure on the border section 0807 of the D 8 motorway, amounting to approximately CZK 20 billion gross (approximately €690 million).</seg>
<seg id="38">Of this amount, €64 million will come from EU Structural Funds (ISPA).</seg>
<seg id="39">The BRH had already examined the planning and construction of the A17 motorway, irrespective of the parallel tests carried out with the NA in the years 2003 to 2005.</seg>
<seg id="40">Of the €277 million of funding for the construction of all three sections of the A17, €277 million will be co-financed by European Funds (ERDF).</seg>
<seg id="41">The Prague-Dresden motorway is part of the Pan-European Transport Corridor IV Dresden - Central and South-Eastern Europe - Istanbul.</seg>
<seg id="42">The D 8 runs from Prague via Usti nad Labem to the Czech/German border,</seg>
<seg id="43">the A 17 from the border to Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="44">At the time of the test, the sections of the motorways close to the border were under construction.</seg>
<seg id="45">Both sections were opened to traffic on 21 December 2006.</seg>
<seg id="46">While the motorway is thus completed on the German side to Dresden, the D 8 remains incomplete on the Czech side, as the section 0805 is still in the planning phase over a length of 16.4 km between Rehlovice and Lovosice.</seg>
<seg id="47">Here the crossing of a landscape protection area in the Bohemian low mountains is planned.</seg>
<seg id="48">According to Czech forecasts from 2001, the volume of traffic in 2008 in section 0807 of the D 8 motorway close to the border will be 22 940 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="49">German forecasts estimate the volume of traffic on the A17 at the Czech border in 2010 at around 25,000 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="50">In 2000, the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic signed a contract for the merger of the German A17 motorway and the Czech motorway D 8 at the common state border by the construction of a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="51">Since both states are involved in the construction of this bridge, this individual construction project was an important aspect of the parallel audits carried out by both courts of auditors.</seg>
<seg id="52">Cooperation between BRH and NNÉ</seg>
<seg id="53">From mid-2005, the two courts of auditors held joint reflections on cooperation in the audit of the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway.</seg>
<seg id="54">Both sides had important reasons for this cooperation:</seg>
<seg id="55">1.</seg>
<seg id="56">Germany partly finances the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="57">Planning and construction are the property of the Czech Road Construction Administration.</seg>
<seg id="58">There was no possibility for the BRH to examine this construction project itself.</seg>
<seg id="59">2.</seg>
<seg id="60">The NA had no comparative data to assess whether the funds were used sparingly with regard to the total construction costs of the bridges and tunnels on the D 8.</seg>
<seg id="61">3.</seg>
<seg id="62">The NA Né also had to examine the effectiveness of the expenditure. To this end, the main technical parameters of the bridges and tunnels should be examined, which should ensure the same quality of use on both sides of the border.</seg>
<seg id="63">Following preparatory negotiations, the Presidents of the two Courts of Auditors concluded an agreement on the coordination of the audits of the Prague-Dresden motorway on 4 January 2006.</seg>
<seg id="64">The auditors of both courts met in the course of 2006 at intervals of approximately six to eight weeks.</seg>
<seg id="65">In doing so, they dealt with current problems and tasks. They developed a uniform methodology for auditing bridge and tunnel prices, exchanged test results on the construction of the border bridge and produced joint reports.</seg>
<seg id="66">The ongoing exchange of information was essential in the cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="67">While the BRH was mainly concerned with the comparison of the technical parameters of bridges and tunnels as well as the procurement procedures, the NKA mainly developed the methodology for the analysis of bridge and tunnel prices.</seg>
<seg id="68">In Germany and the Czech Republic, the legal basis for financial control differs, and thus also in the way in which the two courts of auditors complete their audits.</seg>
<seg id="69">For this reason, both authorities prepared separate national reports on their audit results.</seg>
<seg id="70">This report takes into account the results of the two parallel tests.</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation ends with the signing of a final communiqué in the first half of 2007.</seg>
<seg id="72">Construction of the border bridge</seg>
<seg id="73">In the 2000 treaty, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany agreed to complete the border bridge in 2005 if possible.</seg>
<seg id="74">They later postponed the date by mutual agreement until the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="75">RMD acted as the contractor for the construction project.</seg>
<seg id="76">Germany co-finances the construction of bridges at 42.13%.</seg>
<seg id="77">Initially, the RMD provided for a prestressed concrete construction for the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="78">In 1999, however, RMD and its German partner agreed on the construction of a steel composite structure.</seg>
<seg id="79">They justified this decision by reducing the number of pairs of pillars from seven to five and the associated environmental benefits for the valley.</seg>
<seg id="80">In addition, a comparative calculation of the RMD had identified the steel composite structure as the more cost-effective solution.</seg>
<seg id="81">However, this was due to a calculation error.</seg>
<seg id="82">The calculation was based on a length of the new steel composite structure of only 397 m,</seg>
<seg id="83">in fact, it is 5% longer.</seg>
<seg id="84">During the procurement procedure, the RMD made serious errors,</seg>
<seg id="85">by insufficiently preparing the procurement documents and describing both evaluation criteria and sub-criteria inaccurately.</seg>
<seg id="86">These errors led to subjective and ambiguous assessments by the evaluation committee and the Director General of the RMD.</seg>
<seg id="87">A losing tenderer challenged the outcome of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="88">The subsequent investigation by the Czech Antitrust Office delayed the signing of the construction contract for the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="89">As a result, the summer construction season following the supply review was lost in 2004 and the available total construction time was shortened.</seg>
<seg id="90">The contractor agreed to build the bridge in less time. This led to a significant increase in prices.</seg>
<seg id="91">Among the measures offered were the double assembly of the superstructures, the modification of the pillar shape and the construction of an assembly hall.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition, the contractor was unable to procure the steel grade originally envisaged.</seg>
<seg id="93">The new steel grade – the higher cost of which the client alone bore around €4 million – made it possible to shorten the construction time planned for corrosion protection and thus the overall construction time.</seg>
<seg id="94">Compared to the offer price of approx. € 18.3 million net, the acceleration measures and further additions will significantly increase the total construction costs of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="95">The shortened construction time alone led to a price increase of around € 5.9 million.</seg>
<seg id="96">The costs are currently around € 25.9 million net without price grouting (as of October 2006).</seg>
<seg id="97">Comparison of the prices of bridges and tunnels</seg>
<seg id="98">Both courts examined the bridge prices on the D 8 and the A 17 in order to identify the bridges, which were characterized by particularly high prices and to compare the bridge prices on the German and Czech sides.</seg>
<seg id="99">The study was based on mathematical statistical methods.</seg>
<seg id="100">The tunnels on the D 8 were compared with similar tunnels on the German adrena a71, A 38 and A 4 motorways, as there were no comparable tunnels on the A17.</seg>
<seg id="101">In preparing this part of the examination, it was important to define the price concept in detail.</seg>
<seg id="102">For the comparison of bridge prices, both courts agreed on detailed specifications, such as: to use the current price paid for the bridge without VAT.</seg>
<seg id="103">(VAT rates in the Czech Republic and Germany vary and may change), not to take into account the cost of special start-up measures, to use the Rate of the European Central Bank of 30.12.2005 for currency conversion. (29 CZK = 1 €).</seg>
<seg id="104">Bridges of various types (steel concrete, prestressed concrete, steel composite and steel) and different sizes are available on both the D 8 and the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="105">In order to ensure the comparability of the tested bridge structures, the bridges were grouped according to their design.</seg>
<seg id="106">The analyses also took into account the bridge size within these groups.</seg>
<seg id="107">Concrete bridges (20 bridges on the D 8 and 36 bridges on the A 17) were by far the most common on both sides of the border.</seg>
<seg id="108">The study focused on this type of bridge, as the size of the sample allowed the use of mathematical statistical methods and improved the reliability of the results.</seg>
<seg id="109">The study showed that the m2 price of the concrete bridges on the D 8 / A 17 depends on the bridge size (length, road surface): the larger the bridge, the lower the square meter price.</seg>
<seg id="110">For German bridges, the correlation between price and size is more pronounced than for Czech bridges (see figures below).</seg>
<seg id="111">On the A 17 two bridges could be found, on the D 8 four bridges with significantly increased prices.</seg>
<seg id="112">These bridges were determined partly by a method for determining significant deviations within a sample and partly by regression analysis of the correlation between bridge price and size (atypically expensive bridges can be identified based on the distance to the regression curve).</seg>
<seg id="113">However, the atypically high price of these bridges should only serve as a clue as to which bridges to focus on.</seg>
<seg id="114">In order to draw definitive conclusions, the reasons for the respective high price must be determined on a case-by-case basis.</seg>
<seg id="115">This could be due, for example, to uneconomic administrative action, but also to the requirements for the protection of the environment or other legitimate reasons.</seg>
<seg id="116">Taking into account the larger average length of Czech concrete bridges compared to the German ones (see Table 1), the proven negative correlation between the price of bridges and the length suggested that Czech concrete bridges were cheaper.</seg>
<seg id="117">This was also supported by lower labour costs in the Czech Republic compared to Germany.</seg>
<seg id="118">However, the evaluation of the results showed that the price of the concrete bridges on the D 8 is higher than on the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="119">Two reasons for this were identified during joint discussions:</seg>
<seg id="120">1.</seg>
<seg id="121">In Germany, construction contracts for bridges are mainly awarded separately.</seg>
<seg id="122">This also allows medium-sized companies to participate in the award competition.</seg>
<seg id="123">In the Czech Republic, many bridges are awarded as part of larger contracts for the construction of several kilometres of motorway sections.</seg>
<seg id="124">Orders of this size cannot be handled by medium-sized companies.</seg>
<seg id="125">2.</seg>
<seg id="126">In the Czech Republic, the variety of bridge constructions built is greater than in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="127">In this context, the NKA noted that the construction of bridges is determined long before construction begins,</seg>
<seg id="128">already when the RMD submits its application for planning approval.</seg>
<seg id="129">At this time, it selects a specific bridge construction variant from several alternatives. However, economic efficiency plays a minor role in this decision.</seg>
<seg id="130">Only a thorough analysis of the construction sectors of both countries would have made it possible to reach a definitive conclusion with regard to bridge prices in the Czech Republic and Germany. However, this would have exceeded the scope of that examination.</seg>
<seg id="131">The border bridge is the most expensive steel composite bridge on the D 8 and A 17.</seg>
<seg id="132">The prices for the tunnels on the D 8 are about twice as high as in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="133">However, a comparison of the technical parameters between the tunnels on the D 8 and the tunnels in Germany did not reveal any significant difference.</seg>
<seg id="134">The significant price differences may be the result of underdeveloped competition for tunnelling in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="135">However, the small number of tunnels did not allow generalconclusions.</seg>
<seg id="136">Economic efficiency and effectiveness of the Dresden-Prague motorway</seg>
<seg id="137">The independent Czech Republic was founded in 1993.</seg>
<seg id="138">In the same year, the government adopted the plan for the expansion of the motorway network.</seg>
<seg id="139">The plan was to gradually extend the D8 from Prague to the state border with Germany.</seg>
<seg id="140">The section 0805 was to be built through the Bohemian Low Mountains in front of the border section 0807.</seg>
<seg id="141">The Czech Republic finances d8 under programme financing.</seg>
<seg id="142">In programme number 327 220 "Construction of the motorway D 8 Prague - Czech German border" defines two objectives:</seg>
<seg id="143">1.</seg>
<seg id="144">as a national objective: to improve the link between Prague and sti nad Labem;</seg>
<seg id="145">2.</seg>
<seg id="146">as an international destination: the connection between Prague and Berlin as part of the Pan-European Transport Corridor IV BerlinIstanbul.</seg>
<seg id="147">The programme provided for the construction of the section leading through the Bohemian Low Mountains to be completed in June 2008 and the construction of section 0807 close to the border in June 2007.</seg>
<seg id="148">It should be noted that the end of the construction work is not identical to the time of commissioning.</seg>
<seg id="149">The NKA noted that the planning approval decision had already been issued for the construction of the section leading through the Bohemian Low Mountains.</seg>
<seg id="150">Environmental groups have appealed against this decision.</seg>
<seg id="151">A final judgment is pending.</seg>
<seg id="152">In comparison with the timetable provided for in the programme documentation, it could therefore not be ruled out that the completion of section No 0805 could be delayed by several years.</seg>
<seg id="153">In the summer of 2006, the Czech Ministry of Transport proposed a postponement of the completion date of construction phase No.0805 to 2010.</seg>
<seg id="154">As a result, the construction of the section close to the border did not achieve the national objective of improving the link between Prague and Usti nad Labem.</seg>
<seg id="155">The RMD carried out a cost-effectiveness study of section 0807 of the D 8 and section No.0805 by the Bohemian Low Mountains between 1999 and 2001.</seg>
<seg id="156">As an investment cost, it set an investment cost of around €639 million for both sections No. 0805 and No. 0807.</seg>
<seg id="157">Table 2: Results of the economic analysis (EIRR = internal rate of interest)</seg>
<seg id="158">Variant Opening of all planned motorways and expressways, as well as both D 8sections in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="159">Traffic in the northern part of the border section 18 000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="160">Opening of all planned motorways and expressways, as well as both D 8sections in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="161">Traffic in the northern part of the border section 22 000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="162">Opening of all planned motorways and expressways, as well as both D 8sections in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="163">Traffic in the northern part of the border section 25 000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="164">The 2001 economic efficiency study was based on the assumption that the section close to the border and the section leading through the Bohemian low mountain range are interspersed at the same time.</seg>
<seg id="165">At the time of the examination it was obvious that the section through the Bohemian Low Mountains would not be opened on the original date.</seg>
<seg id="166">This reduces the above EIRR values.</seg>
<seg id="167">The costs of both sections as at 31 December 2005 amounted to € 897 million excluding VAT, which is 27.4% higher than in the 2001 economic situation.</seg>
<seg id="168">There is also a risk that section 0805 will have a different more complex process, which would affect the economic viability of the project.</seg>
<seg id="169">The economic analysis showed that the construction of both sections of the motorway, with a daily traffic volume of at least 18 000 vehicles per day in 2010, is economically justified. The forecast for 2008 had predicted 22 940 cars per day.</seg>
<seg id="170">However, a study on diversion routes as an alternative to the missing section through the Bohemian Low Mountains estimates traffic volumes of 12 600 to 13 750 vehicles per day in 2007. The project is then below the economic efficiency limit.</seg>
<seg id="171">A higher volume of traffic on the routes intended to replace the missing section with the Bohemian Low Mountains is likely to lead to congestion and thus increased external costs, which were not taken into account in the initial economic analysis.</seg>
<seg id="172">The abovementioned reduction in revenue and an increase in costs means that the already low EIRR for the construction of the border section of the D8 will not be achieved.</seg>
<seg id="173">The construction of the section of the D 8 border is therefore uneconomical.</seg>
<seg id="174">Costs were also increased in the construction of the A 17, as in the construction of the two sections of the D 8.</seg>
<seg id="175">As part of the overall economic assessment for the 1992 Federal Transport Route Plan, the Federal Ministry responsible for transport assumed investment costs of around € 320 million.</seg>
<seg id="176">It thus established a benefit/cost ratio of 4.6.</seg>
<seg id="177">In the meantime, the costs have increased to around € 670 million and the benefit/cost ratio has been reduced by more than half.</seg>
<seg id="178">Irrespective of the parallel tests carried out with the NCA between 2003 and 2005, the BRH had examined the cost-effectiveness of the planning and construction of the A17 motorway.</seg>
<seg id="179">It found that the authority responsible for the permit requested an unnecessary landscape tunnel for the third section of the A17.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the course of the audit, the BRH succeeded in convincing the Federal Ministry and the Road Construction Administration of the excess fluidity of the landscape tunnel.</seg>
<seg id="181">This prevented €10 million in construction costs and €150,000 in annual operating costs.</seg>
<seg id="182">When examining the first section of the A17, the BRH found that the construction work was insufficiently prepared.</seg>
<seg id="183">The following example illustrates this:</seg>
<seg id="184">During the planning phase, the road construction administration refrained from detecting the condition of the rock on the surface of the Dölzschen wall, as it was difficult to access.</seg>
<seg id="185">It was only when the tunnelling reached the wall that she made up for it.</seg>
<seg id="186">This showed that the rock was more weathered than was assumed in the tender.</seg>
<seg id="187">Extensive measures such as anchorages, injections and stone-fall protection nets for around €3.3 million were necessary.</seg>
<seg id="188">The road construction administration not only borne the costs of additional, already necessary ice sials such as securing the Dölzschen wall, but also for those that would not have been necessary if the construction had been properly prepared.</seg>
<seg id="189">This includes expenses due to disrupted construction processes (€3.2 million), additional induction of the drivage team (€0.5 million) and increased wages and material prices due to the extension of the construction period (€7 million).</seg>
<seg id="190">This additional expenditure of around €10.7 million is not offset by any lasting added value.</seg>
<seg id="191">The BRH took these and other measures as an opportunity to call on the Federal Ministry to better exercise its supervision of major road construction measures.</seg>
<seg id="192">In this context, it should insist that road construction administrations introduce quality assurance systems.</seg>
<seg id="193">Benefits of the cooperation for BRH and NNÉ The cooperation met the expectations of both courts of auditors.</seg>
<seg id="194">The BRH received insights into the planning, procurement and implementation of the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="195">Both courts developed a database on bridge and tunnel prices, which will be helpful in future audits.</seg>
<seg id="196">The NA noted that the main structural parameters for the bridges, tunnels and roadway of the D 8 are no different from those of the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="197">The auditors of both courts of auditors involved in the cooperation gained valuable experience which will be useful in future audits.</seg>
