<seg id="1">Public procurement of works and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint report of the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NA) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and overview</seg>
<seg id="4">The award of services by contracting authorities is of great importance both for the State and for the economy.</seg>
<seg id="5">The state's task is to use public funds as economically and sparingly as possible and to ensure fair and regulated competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), the award of services by contracting authorities is an important part of the creation of a single economic area.</seg>
<seg id="7">In order to ensure largely unrestricted competition across borders, contracting authorities must comply with EU requirements for their contracts from certain value limits (thresholds).</seg>
<seg id="8">To this end, EU Member States must transposed and apply EU public procurement law into national law.</seg>
<seg id="9">This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="10">Below the EU thresholds, it is up to individual countries to regulate the award of public contracts themselves.</seg>
<seg id="11">The award of services is also a corruption-prone area.</seg>
<seg id="12">In view of the inherently high potential for damage, contracting authorities must therefore take appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and undue favours in the award of their contracts.</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NA) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed to carry out parallel audits for both eu-wide awarding of construction services and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="14">The audits focused on the application of EU public procurement law, which is transposed into national rules, and the prevention of corruption in the award of construction services in construction and road construction or transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="15">Procurement below the EU thresholds was also considered in terms of anti-corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="16">The audit results of both Courts of Auditors are summarised in this Joint Report.</seg>
<seg id="17">The report will also be addressed to international bodies, such as the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="18">Examination areas and audited bodies The evaluations of the Federal Audit Office on the listed topics are mainly based on cross-sectional audits carried out in 2011/2012 by the building administrations responsible for the road and construction of the federal government in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="19">In doing so, he examined, for example, the construction of motorways and major construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="20">In addition, the Federal Audit Office used results from previous investigations.</seg>
<seg id="21">The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic based its evaluations on audit findings from 2008 to 2011. The audits included construction work in road construction, rail transport, hydraulic engineering, building construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.) and other construction areas in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="22">In Germany, the procurement of public contracts by the federal government is mainly carried out by the building administrations of the federal states.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the Czech Republic, the State Building Administration is centrally responsible for transport infrastructure procurement.</seg>
<seg id="24">In the construction sector, the contracts are carried out decentrally by those bodies which use state budgets.</seg>
<seg id="25">In both countries, freelancers are also involved in sub-sectors of the procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="26">In comparing the evaluations, differences in procurement law and in the market structure for construction services of both countries must be taken into account.</seg>
<seg id="27">Structure of public procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="28">In Germany, the implementation of E-wide procurement procedures is laid down in laws and regulations.</seg>
<seg id="29">Procurement procedures limited to the national sphere are governed by budgetary law and the administrative rules based on it.</seg>
<seg id="30">For both EU-wide and national procurement, many supplementary individual rules are also provided by internal administrative provisions,</seg>
<seg id="31">such as the so-called "procurement manuals" of the Confederation, in which the legal requirements are supplemented or further formulated in compliance with the law on public procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure is governed exclusively by the Public Procurement Act and other legal provisions applicable to both the area above and below the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="33">Procurement law was substantially amended in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new rules increased transparency in the use of public funds, allowed for greater competition and limited the possibilities of corruption in the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="35">Basic features of public procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">In both countries, EU-wide procurement is subject in particular to the open procedure, the open procedure and the negotiated procedure.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, measures below the EU threshold are subject to national procurement types (public procurement, restricted tendering, hands-free procurement), but which are broadly in line with the above-mentioned EU-wide procurement types.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement law in Germany is characterised by the principle of the primacy of open procedure (in the case of EU-wide contracts) and public procurement (for national contracts).</seg>
<seg id="39">In the open procedure and in the public tender, any interested company may submit an offer.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another key feature of German public procurement law is the promotion of medium-sized enterprises.</seg>
<seg id="41">For this purpose, the main purpose is to divide an overall construction project into specialist and partial lots.</seg>
<seg id="42">The individual award of these lots is intended to enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.</seg>
<seg id="43">Both of the above-mentioned features of German public procurement law are proven tools for achieving economic results.</seg>
<seg id="44">More than 330,000 construction companies employ 1.9 million people in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="45">In the Czech Republic, EU-wide procurement procedures are also applicable to construction projects below the EU threshold.</seg>
<seg id="46">One exception is the simplified procedure, which allows a less stringent procedure to be applied below the thresholds and, under certain conditions, to a less stringent procedure.</seg>
<seg id="47">Czech public procurement law contains provisions, in line with EU law, that contracts should be concluded if competition is guaranteed and a favourable price is achieved.</seg>
<seg id="48">The current legal provisions in the Czech Republic allow the contracting authorities to choose between the open procedure and the restricted procedure.</seg>
<seg id="49">There are more than 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, of which about 1,900 are companies with 20 or more employees.</seg>
<seg id="50">Volume of construction of contracting authorities and shares of procurement types in both countries</seg>
<seg id="51">In Germany, the total construction volume in 2011 amounted to EUR 307 billion.</seg>
<seg id="52">Of this amount, EUR 45.5 billion was accounted for by public works (15%), which includes, in addition to federal construction, the construction measures of the federal states and municipalities.</seg>
<seg id="53">The federal construction volume in construction and long-distance road construction (excluding rail infrastructure and hydraulic engineering) amounted to EUR 8.5 billion.</seg>
<seg id="54">The volume of contracts for construction and road construction by the Federal Government was distributed among the award types in 2011 as follows: 80.7% open procedures and public tenders, 12.7% of non-open procedures and restricted tenders and 6.6% negotiated and hands-free contracts.</seg>
<seg id="55">Of these, 33.2% were European-wide contracts.</seg>
<seg id="56">The volume of public works projects in the Czech Republic amounted to EUR 4.7 billion in 2011, which represented about 25% of the total volume of all construction projects in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="57">In 2009, the volume amounted to EUR 7.8 billion, representing 37% of the total construction volume.</seg>
<seg id="58">Breakdown by type of award for 2011: 65.1% open procedures 14.3% non-public procedures 9.5% Negotiated procedures 8.4% Simplified procedures for contract volumes below the 2.7% threshold</seg>
