<seg id="115">Fundamentals of EU public procurement law and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="116">EU public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="117">In order to ensure unrestricted competition within the European Union with the free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, inter alia, the Procurement Coordination Directive and the Remedies Directive, which had to be transposed into national law by the Member States.</seg>
<seg id="118">The general principles of public procurement in the European Union are, in particular, the principle of competition, the principle of equal treatment or the prohibition of discrimination and the requirement of transparency.</seg>
<seg id="119">In order to achieve these objectives, the Procurement Coordination Directive lays down specific rules for construction work to be awarded across the EU.</seg>
<seg id="120">For this purpose, their expected order amounts must reach or exceed the current amount of 5,000,000 euros.</seg>
<seg id="121">The rules concern, in particular, the content of the procurement documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, the observance of deadlines, inter alia, the receipt of tenders, the documentation of the procurement procedure, the requirements which may be made on the qualifications of candidates and the Remedies Directive forms the basis for the legal protection of candidates and tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="122">In the event of possible infringements of public procurement law, undertakings concerned may have the decisions of contracting authorities reviewed in review procedures.</seg>
<seg id="123">Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the European Union directives into national law.</seg>
<seg id="124">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="125">Importance of the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="126">In both countries, there is no legal definition of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="127">In general, corruption is the abuse of a trust for private gain,</seg>
<seg id="128">which is usually initiated by the beneficiaries of those decisions.</seg>
<seg id="129">Corruption can hinder competition and cause significant economic damage.</seg>
<seg id="130">It is estimated that the global costs of corruption amount to 5% of world economic output.</seg>
<seg id="131">For the European Union, the cost is estimated at 1%.</seg>
<seg id="132">In the case of contracting authorities, restrictive agreements or unfair conduct may call into question confidence in the integrity and functioning of the administration.</seg>
<seg id="133">Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="134">In doing so, they must check the organisation of their administrations' organisation of activities in areas at high risk of corruption in order to take appropriate safeguards against corruption there.</seg>
<seg id="135">Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the vulnerability of decision-making processes to corrupt abuses.</seg>
<seg id="136">The award of public works is generally regarded as a particularly corrupt field of work.</seg>
<seg id="137">Measures to prevent corruption</seg>
<seg id="138">In Germany, corruption – in particular bribery and bribery, as well as the acceptance and approval of benefits – is prosecuted under criminal and labour law.</seg>
<seg id="139">In order to prevent corruption, the Federal Government has issued a directive and recommendations on the prevention of corruption12 in the Federal Administration. In addition to risk analysis, the following basic principles must be observed for the procurement sector: priority for public tenders and open procedures, multi-eyes principle and transparency, basic separation of planning, procurement and settlement, precise and complete documentation of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="140">In addition, other anti-corruption requirements have been incorporated into the procurement legislation.</seg>
<seg id="141">In 2011, for example, the competent Federal Ministry for Contracts for Contracts for Contracts in the field of federal highways introduced an electronically-based control system,</seg>
<seg id="142">with the procurement data, such as estimated costs and order sums, as well as information on the freelancers involved, information is collected nationwide and evaluated for abnormalities.</seg>
<seg id="143">Corruption is also prosecuted in the Czech Republic under criminal and labour law.</seg>
<seg id="144">The legal requirements of transparency and equal treatment of tenderers, as well as the prohibition of all discrimination, are the most important foundations for the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="145">For public procurement, the Czech government has defined anti-corruption measures in an anti-corruption strategy paper for the years 2011 to 2012 and updated them for the years 2013 to 2014.</seg>
<seg id="146">Some of the measures recommended in it have already been transposed into national public procurement law and related administrative provisions14.</seg>
<seg id="147">The new legislation essentially contains the following rules: reduction of the thresholds for smaller contracts, obligation to publish contracts in good time by the contracting authority, including the indication of the grounds for tendering, prohibition of the restriction of the number of tenderers in restricted procedures and thus abolishthe possibility of selecting tenderers by means of lottery procedures, introduction of the obligation to publish contract documents and all annexes, introduction of the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors.</seg>
<seg id="148">Examination results for the various stages of the procurement procedure</seg>
<seg id="149">Procurement documents</seg>
<seg id="150">Procurement documents Procurement documents must contain all the information that tenderers need to prepare a proper tender.</seg>
<seg id="151">In particular, the procurement documents must enable an accurate calculation.</seg>
<seg id="152">Tenderers must not be given risks that cannot be calculated on their part.</seg>
<seg id="153">The procurement documents consist in particular of the specifications and the terms of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="154">In addition, they contain the requirements for proving the qualification (suitability) of the tenderers and the criteria that are relevant for the selection of the most economical tender.</seg>
<seg id="155">Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="156">The requirements of EU law on procurement documents are addressed in particular to the technical specifications.</seg>
<seg id="157">These must be equally accessible to all tenderers and should limit competition as little as possible.</seg>
<seg id="158">The service description must in principle be product-neutral.</seg>
<seg id="159">Therefore, information on products or manufacturers as part of the service description is only permitted under strict conditions.</seg>
<seg id="160">Avoiding restrictive requirements in procurement documents is also a fundamental principle of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="161">In addition, unclear or inaccurate information in the procurement documents must be avoided, since it opens up scope for speculation in the preparation of tenders and for manipulation of their valuation.</seg>
<seg id="162">Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="163">Same or similar rules In both countries, the EU legal requirements for technical specifications have been transposed into national law.</seg>
<seg id="164">In principle, the services must be advertised in a product-neutral manner without manufacturer requirements.</seg>
<seg id="165">In the service descriptions, the individual services must normally be broken down in detail into performance units with the respective quantities.</seg>
