<seg id="724">In the case of open and restricted procedures or public and restricted invitations to tender, the contracting authority may not deviate from the content of the tender at the time of conclusion of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="725">The losing tenderers shall be informed in a timely manner of the award decision and of the reasons for not taking their tenders into account.</seg>
<seg id="726">Procurement procedures may be terminated only under certain conditions, e.g. where the bid prices are inflated or the tenders do not meet the requirements of the invitation to tender.</seg>
<seg id="727">Different regulations</seg>
<seg id="728">In the Czech Republic, the 10- or 15-day obligation to provide information and wait before awarding the contract also exists for construction work not to be awarded throughout Europe.</seg>
<seg id="729">In Germany, these requirements apply only to EU-wide procurement.</seg>
<seg id="730">In the case of other proceedings in Germany, tenderers may not be informed of the award decision until the contract has been awarded.</seg>
<seg id="731">In the Czech Republic, a procurement procedure must be annulled if only one bid has been received or only one offer could be evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="732">In Germany, the contract must also be awarded in the case of only a single valuable tender, provided that it complies with the conditions of the invitation to tender and is economical.</seg>
<seg id="733">Key test results</seg>
<seg id="734">BRH</seg>
<seg id="735">In the case of the contracts examined, there were only a few complaints at the time of the conclusion of the procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="736">In some cases, companies received letters of order in EU-wide contracts before the expiry of the information deadlines, which may result in the invalidity of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="737">In individual cases, order letters after open procedures also contained content that differed from the content of the offer, such as changed dates.</seg>
<seg id="738">In several cases, contracting entities did not comply with the award deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="739">In an open procedure, therefore, a contracting authority awarded the contract for the second most favourable tender, since an undertaking with a 50% cheaper tender was no longer prepared to carry out the services at the price originally offered after the end of the contract period.</seg>
<seg id="740">NKO</seg>
<seg id="741">In the case of a construction project in the higher education sector, the contracting authority deviated from the tenderer's offer in the contract.</seg>
<seg id="742">In some contracts, for example for road maintenance construction, the construction of a motorway and a bypass road, the contracting authorities concluded the contracts after the statutory deadline.</seg>
<seg id="743">In the award of works for the redevelopment of former military sites, the contracting authority forwarded the notification of the award of the contract to all tenderers only after the statutory deadline had expired.</seg>
<seg id="744">Summary findings</seg>
<seg id="745">Both countries have implemented the EU's requirements for the completion of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="746">The legal protection of the losing candidates or bidders increases the scope of the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="747">The scope of legal protection in Czech public procurement law is also extended to contracts below the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="748">In both countries, overruns in the deadlines for awarding contracts have been found.</seg>
<seg id="749">This can lead to economic disadvantages and increase the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="750">Construction administrations should avoid the shortcomings identified in the conclusion of their procurement procedures in the future.</seg>
<seg id="751">Documentation, reporting and reporting requirements</seg>
<seg id="752">Procurement procedures shall be documented in a comprehensible manner during their various stages with regard to the relevant findings and the reasons for each decision.</seg>
<seg id="753">In EU-wide procedures, the contracts awarded must be made public.</seg>
<seg id="754">The order data is also recorded in an EU statistic.</seg>
<seg id="755">Eu law requirements and the prevention of corruption The documentation of procurement procedures implements a fundamental requirement of the EU's wide-spread transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="756">A carefully and promptly prepared documentation only makes it possible to trace the award decisions.</seg>
<seg id="757">In particular, it also serves to provide effective legal protection for tenderers in the case of procurement above the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="758">Proper documentation is also an essential element in preventing corruption, as the compulsion to justify procurement decisions in detail significantly narrows the scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">The notice of a contract awarded in an EU-wide procurement procedure must be sent by the relevant contracting authority to the EU Office for Official Publications within 48 days.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Office publishes the notices in the Official Journal of the EU and thus also implements the transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting authorities must also collect the essential data of their procurement procedures and report them to the EU Commission through the relevant national ministries.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the EU Commission produces an annual EU statistic to provide an overview of the development of the internal market in construction.</seg>
<seg id="763">Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Same or similar rules</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries have fully transposed EU legislation on documentation and reporting obligations into national law.</seg>
<seg id="766">The rules on documentation and reporting for EU statistics are largely the same in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Different regulations</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the obligation to publish contracts awarded is not only limited to EU-wide contracts, but also extends to other procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The publication period is reduced to 15 days.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, in addition to EU-wide contracts, there is a duty to publish only in the case of restricted tenders and, in the case of hands-free contracts, contracts with a value limit of EUR 25,000 or EUR 15,000 without VAT (so-called ex-post transparency).</seg>
<seg id="771">Below these value limits and in the case of public tenders, only the undertakings involved in the competition procedure shall receive information on the award of contracts.</seg>
<seg id="772">Key test results</seg>
<seg id="773">BRH</seg>
<seg id="774">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">A large number of the procurement procedures examined were not fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The award notes did not contain all the necessary information, such as to justify product specifications or to refer to national regulations.</seg>
<seg id="777">In a procurement procedure, the contracting authority did not explain why it awarded the contract to an undertaking, even though its tender did not contain evidence to be made compulsory.</seg>
<seg id="778">In a few cases, the documents of the contracting authorities did not contain all the evidence necessary for the documentation of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="779">Notices of procurement</seg>
<seg id="780">In some EU-wide procurement procedures, contracting authorities failed to publicise the awardof contracts.</seg>
<seg id="781">Other procurement procedures lacked evidence that the contracting authorities had made the contracts awarded public.</seg>
<seg id="782">Reporting and reporting obligations</seg>
<seg id="783">The statistical statements consulted contained the minimum data required. They had been prepared and sent on time.</seg>
<seg id="784">Ex-post transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">In most cases, the audited building administrations published the contract data of the completed procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="786">However, a construction administration did not publish this data due to a transmission error.</seg>
<seg id="787">The building administration only noticed this error after six months,</seg>
<seg id="788">so that the contract data of the procurement procedures concluded so far have not been published.</seg>
<seg id="789">NKO</seg>
<seg id="790">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">In the case of construction work for the organisation of a major sporting event, the documentation of the procurement procedures was considerablely flawed. These were mainly inaccurate information, such as incorrect quotation prices in the minutes of the evaluation commissions.</seg>
<seg id="792">In addition, some protocols of the opening of tenders were not signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Notices of procurement</seg>
<seg id="794">In the case of several road construction projects, notices of contracts awarded were published late or not at all.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary findings</seg>
<seg id="796">The rules on documentation and reporting and reporting requirements are broadly in line with the rules in both countries and implement the EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="797">This will, in principle, ensure the transparency of procurement procedures, including the award of contracts.</seg>
<seg id="798">The rules to be applied in the Czech Republic for publication go a little further than those in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="799">The shortcomings in documentation and notices identified significantly limited the orruption-preventive effect of these instruments in the respective procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="800">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFBlank</seg>
<seg id="801">Construction administrations should further improve the transparency of their procurement procedures and procurement and fully comply with their reporting and reporting obligations.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">The parallel audits carried out by the NCA and the BRH focused on two priorities, which are essential for the award of works by contracting authorities in the Czech Republic and Germany: the application of EU procurement rules and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="804">The requirements of EU law will allow for cross-border competition to create a Single European Market.</seg>
<seg id="805">Anti-corruption measures are not only aimed at preventing or at least reducing corruption. They are also intended to avert economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.</seg>
<seg id="806">The audit findings of the two courts of auditors on the application of the procurement rules in both countries and the comparison of these rules reveal information on commonalities and differences which may help both countries to develop their procurement law and its application.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU public procurement rules</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries have transposed the EU's requirements for the award of works into national law.</seg>
<seg id="809">This provides an important common basis in the Czech Republic and Germany for the award of works and the consideration of the essential requirements of competition, the equal treatment of the undertakings involved and the transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">The building administrations of both countries have in some cases subject these bids to further administrative regulations.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has largely transferred the requirements for the construction works to be awarded to the EU to its nationally regulated procurement procedures below the EU threshold.</seg>
<seg id="812">However, the audits carried out by the Courts of Auditors have shown that the building authorities have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.</seg>
<seg id="813">The building administration in Germany should further improve the quality of its procurement procedures in order to be able to eliminate the complaints identified when implementing the EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">The audits in the Czech Republic have shown, in particular, risks affecting the economic viability of contracts.</seg>
<seg id="815">For example, incomplete service descriptions necessitated additional services, which were often awarded in breach of the law. In addition, the cost assessments were usually insufficiently prepared. Excessive qualification requirements also reduced the number of potential bidders and restricted competition, particularly in the case of transport structures.</seg>
<seg id="816">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="817">The investigations have not been aimed at uncovering corruption cases,</seg>
<seg id="818">also because the Courts of Auditors do not have the appropriate instruments for this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, the Courts of Auditors can examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken precautions against corruption and manipulation in the award of works and how these requirements are applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">The two countries have set different priorities for the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="821">In particular, the German regulations provide for largely unrestricted competition, transparency and controls as central elements of the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="822">The Czech rules are aimed above all at increasing the transparency of procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, general principles of the prevention of corruption apply, which the entire Federal Administration must apply.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles are also implemented in the specifications for the award of works and are geared to their specific requirements.</seg>
<seg id="826">In some cases, the relevant rules specify the way in which the requirements for the prevention of corruption must be taken into account in the course of procurement procedures and in the selection of the persons involved.</seg>
<seg id="827">In particular, the BRH considers that the primacy of the principle of open procedure or public tendering is an appropriate instrument for substantially reducing the risk of corruption in the award of works. Restrictions on competition, on the other hand, increase the risk of manipulative interference.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analyses and adequate controls (in particular the multi-eyes principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of procurement procedures, as well as various organisational measures are also effective measures to prevent corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">The BRH therefore does not see any fundamental need for changes to the corresponding requirements of the administrations in the award of works.</seg>
<seg id="830">The rules on the prevention of corruption are largely taken into account in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">The shortcomings identified in some areas have highlighted shortcomings in the implementation of some requirements.</seg>
<seg id="832">Building authorities should further train their employees on the requirements for the prevention of corruption and raise their awareness of this problem even more.</seg>
<seg id="833">A significant part of the complaints related to tasks delegated by the building administrations to freelancers.</seg>
<seg id="834">However, without controls and adequate safeguards, the risk of abuse increases when delegating tasks.</seg>
<seg id="835">Tasks at risk of manipulation and corruption should therefore only be entrusted to third parties if the administration can ensure a sufficient level of protection against improper interference.</seg>
<seg id="836">NKO</seg>
<seg id="837">The Czech Republic adopted an anti-corruption strategy at government level, in which public procurement is the most important component.</seg>
<seg id="838">The Procurement Act and the associated implementing provisions have been substantially amended.</seg>
<seg id="839">The nca's audits took place during the implementation of this strategy.</seg>
<seg id="840">The strategy adopted and the new legal provisions should be effective improvement measures, as the contracting authorities must justify the economic viability of the awarding of contracts, the calculation of expected prices, the adequacy of the qualification requirements, the essential evaluation criteria and the nature of the evaluations, and must properly document and publish all these aspects.</seg>
<seg id="841">Recommendations</seg>
<seg id="842">The NCA and the BRH are generally positive about the implementation of the EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="843">The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that EU competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for the award of works within the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="844">The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at enabling and promoting cross-border competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">In view of the enormous material and ideological damage potential of manipulation and corruption in the award of construction services, both courts of auditors see the building administrations in their countries as being called upon to continue and, if necessary, to improve their measures against corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, the organisation and procedures of procurement procedures should be continuously examined for weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for action and to take appropriate countermeasures.</seg>
<seg id="847">The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the proportion of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased, as open procedures can provide a wider scope for competition and significantly reduce the risk of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="848">Greater distribution of works into lots may also have a favourable effect on bid prices, provided that this results in greater competition with a higher number of bidders.</seg>
<seg id="849">Ensuring the correct conduct of procurement procedures is an essential basis for the efficient procurement activities of contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany, the procurement procedures are carried out by the specialised building administrations. In the Czech Republic, on the other hand, these tasks are carried out by the departments themselves or contractors commissioned by them, with the exception of transport projects.</seg>
<seg id="851">The Courts of Auditors of both countries are concerned to develop the knowledge that is important to them and, if necessary, to bring them to the parliament and government of their country, even after the completion of their joint project.</seg>
<seg id="852">Both Courts of Auditors also believe that the principles of public procurement law set out in this report and its implementation are also of interest at international level to the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI). The principles and findings set out are of general importance in order to effectively counter corruption and to ensure the economic award of works in a well-functioning and fair competition.</seg>
<seg id="853">Equipment</seg>
</p>
