<p>
<seg id="1">Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Report on the control check</seg>
<seg id="3">Preface</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxes are the main source of revenue for public budgets.</seg>
<seg id="5">The activities of the Courts of Auditors should therefore be based on the audit of this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">This applies in particular to VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="7">This alone causes tax losses of an estimated EUR 100 billion per year in the European Union1.</seg>
<seg id="8">At the VI EUROSAI Congress in Bonn in 2005, the participants already stressed the need for enhanced cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">This enables the auditors, for example, to exchange audit approaches and to optimise audit practice.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT (VAT) is particularly suitable for cooperation as it is harmonised within the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="11">In 2006, for the first time, the Courts of Auditors of both countries examined the VAT in parallel.</seg>
<seg id="12">The relevant audit report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">As VAT fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, close cooperation between the Courts of Auditors is needed. This will enable a comprehensive assessment of the appropriate measures taken to effectively address VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="14">The two Courts of Auditors decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit. Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany Report on the control audit</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Examination number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject of audit: (CZ) Administration of THE USt (D) Bilateral audit with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (hereinafter NC), audit</seg>
<seg id="18">Examination objective:</seg>
<seg id="19">- (CZ) Mr President, I would like to The VAT administration and the treatment of selected transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic (CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter Germany) should be examined. In addition, the procedures used by the tax authorities in intergovernmental administrative assistance should be examined.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The audit was intended to evaluate how the tax administration has implemented the recommendations made by the Courts of Auditors.</seg>
<seg id="21">In addition, other examination fields linked to the VAT should be edited.</seg>
<seg id="22">The findings should be compared in order to determine whether tax procedures can be optimised.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audit period was the years 2006 to 2008, including relevant information from the period prior to the audit period until the completion of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel audit</seg>
<seg id="25">The Courts of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed on a verification check on the administration of the VAT.</seg>
<seg id="26">In the previous parallel audit, they had uncovered suspected cases of intra-Community transactions,</seg>
<seg id="27">which made it appropriate to re-examine.</seg>
<seg id="28">On the basis of the audit findings, the two Courts of Auditors made recommendations on the management of the VAT.</seg>
<seg id="29">The aim of the audit was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented. In addition, the suspected cases identified should be investigated.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit also dealt with other issues. These included selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions, mutual administrative assistance in the recovery of VAT claims and VAT audits of large firms.</seg>
<seg id="31">The Courts of Auditors have found that:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous audit</seg>
<seg id="33">• Recommendation 1: The rules for the registration of taxpayers should be harmonised within the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">In the first audit, the Courts of Auditors compared the registration procedures for VAT in the two countries and found differences that caused problems.</seg>
<seg id="35">The Courts of Auditors therefore recommended harmonising the registration of taxpayers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This has also been taken up at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The draft amendment of Council Regulation No 1798/2003 provides for the addition of the current databases in the EU, including a database with the identification number of VAT officers.</seg>
<seg id="38">The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxpayers and their possible deletion.</seg>
<seg id="39">The Courts of Auditors expected Member States to agree, in accordance with their decision in principle, on appropriate arrangements to remove unreliable entrepreneurs from the VAT system as early as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">The latest version of the draft was agreed politically by the Member States in Ecofin.</seg>
<seg id="41">These common rules are no longer included. The two Courts of Auditors regret this.</seg>
<seg id="42">They still consider such rules to be important in order to prevent VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">• Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of summary notifications As a result of the first audit, the Courts of Auditors recommended to the Member States that the Summary Notifications (ZM) should be submitted on a monthly basis in future.</seg>
<seg id="44">The amounts of intra-Community transactions could then be reviewed more quickly.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive 2008/117/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of VAT for the purpose of combating tax fraud in intra-Community transactions shortened the deadline for the submission of the ZM to one month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the CZ, this requirement was implemented by an amendment to the VAT Act, which entered into force on 1 January 2010.</seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, implementation did not enter into force until 1 July 2010. It has thus failed to transpose the obligation to pay the ZM monthly into national law in due time.</seg>
<seg id="48">• Recommendation 3: Data matching of THE VAT pre-registrations and the ZM in Germany for more reliable MIAS data and proposal to examine the merging of procedures for VAT pre-registrations and ZM. The German tax administration has taken up the recommendation made by the Federal Audit Office and set up a working group to work out possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="49">Work is still ongoing.</seg>
<seg id="50">The Federal Audit Office will monitor the further development.</seg>
<seg id="51">• Recommendation 4: Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level During the first audit, the two auditors agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by one Member State alone.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful criteria and elements or approaches of a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="53">Failure to do so will result in fraudsters concentrating on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The Courts of Auditors found that the two Member States apply different risk management systems, which have both strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">The NKU examined the system of information exchange within the EU - EUROCANET, while the Federal Audit Office focused on The German participation in the "Platform for Risk Management".</seg>
<seg id="56">2. Check of selected intra-Community transactions</seg>
<seg id="57">During the first audit, the Courts of Auditors had jointly examined transactions which were doubtful whether they had actually been exported or which had been explained differently by the taxable persons of the two States in the VAT pre-declarations (or VAT declarations) or ZM.</seg>
<seg id="58">The Courts of Auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between the CZ and Germany for the verification check.</seg>
<seg id="59">The audits carried out by the tax authorities (FAD) of both countries were not yet completed at the time of the completion of the first parallel audit.</seg>
<seg id="60">The audit has shown that the tax procedures for these selected transactions have now been completed. The respective tax administrations had taken appropriate measures to this end (including subsequent VAT fixing or the prevention of VAT refunds).</seg>
<seg id="61">3. Examination of selected, particularly risky intra-Community transactions</seg>
<seg id="62">The audit also included high-risk intra-Community transactions between taxable persons in the EU, which were covered by the EUROCANET system.</seg>
<seg id="63">EUROCANET is used to identify risky taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="64">Member States may participate in this scheme on a voluntary basis.</seg>
<seg id="65">The CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET. Germany has a passive status, i.e. it does not participate in the exchange of data under EUROCANET.</seg>
<seg id="66">From the point of view of an active participating State, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.</seg>
<seg id="67">This did not allow information to be obtained as to which suppliers with a German VAT ID would have been classified as highly risky cases.</seg>
<seg id="68">The NKU found both normal transactions and those suspected of VAT fraud, including carousel fraud, in the selected transactions.</seg>
<seg id="69">FäTs were able to examine high-risk sales only to a limited extent. This was particularly the case in the case of so-called 'missing traders', whereby an examination of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to prove fraud to the taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="70">In case of suspected carousel fraud in imports and exports</seg>
<seg id="71">it is recommended that customs and tax authorities cooperate more closely to monitor the identifyability of the goods and their actual routes of transport within the EU to the final customer.</seg>
<seg id="72">Germany and a number of other countries have refused to participate actively in EUROCANET on the grounds that there is not a sufficient legal basis.</seg>
<seg id="73">The Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Audit Office) found that the German tax administration uses other instruments to identify high-risk taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="74">However, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="75">The Council of the EU agreed on a draft regulation,</seg>
<seg id="76">created by EUROFISC.</seg>
<seg id="77">The experience gained so far with EUROCANET should feed into the planned network for combating VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="78">4.Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims</seg>
<seg id="79">Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.</seg>
<seg id="80">Therefore, requests for intergovernmental administrative assistance in the recovery of claims in the CZ and Germany are processed in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="81">The Federal Audit Office and NKU compared the statistics that both Member States provided to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.</seg>
<seg id="82">These statistics contained inconsistencies.</seg>
<seg id="83">The two Courts of Auditors consider it useful to re-discuss statistics at EU level in order to avoid any further inconsistencies in the future.</seg>
<seg id="84">If this is not done, the statistics cannot be used appropriately for comparisons.</seg>
<seg id="85">In addition, the statistics should contain more information on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="86">An analysis of detailed data can help the Commission to support Member States in their efforts to combat VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="87">Both Courts of Auditors consider that Member States with a low recovery rate should endeavour to achieve at least the average recovery rate.</seg>
<seg id="88">The Commission should support the Member States in this if they so wish.</seg>
<seg id="89">5. USt test for large companies</seg>
<seg id="90">The Courts of Auditors analysed the legal situation with regard to the VAT audit of large companies in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="91">In addition, they used a questionnaire to collect information from the tax authorities which they considered important in this context.</seg>
<seg id="92">It became clear that the situation in both countries is different.</seg>
<seg id="93">The CZ has a system for the selection of risky cases that incorporates a large amount of relevant data (including information on VAT audits, balance sheet data and profit and loss accounts).</seg>
<seg id="94">As a result, the VAT control can be effectively controlled and analyzed.</seg>
<seg id="95">In 2012, a special tax office for large enterprises is to be set up.</seg>
<seg id="96">Germany does not yet have a comparable system. This makes it difficult to control and analyze VAT control as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="97">The German tax administration focuses more on the selection of relevant individual cases and relies in particular on data from the VAT pre-registrations or VAT declarations and the ZM.</seg>
<seg id="98">Various risk management components that are to be improved support the evaluation of this data.</seg>
<seg id="99">3. Examination procedure</seg>
<seg id="100">3.1 Examination procedure in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="101">Division II - State budget revenue and regional divisions IX Pilsen, X'eské Budjovice, XIII Brno and XV Ostrava audited between May 2009 and February 2010.</seg>
<seg id="102">Audited bodies were the Czech Ministry of Finance and 25 FECs: Tax Office (FA) Brno II, FA Brno III, FA Brno IV, FA in Béeclav, FA in Doma lice, FA in Hodonin, FA in Hradec Krslové, FA in Cheb, FA in Jablonec nad Nisou, FA in Karlovy Vary, FA in Kralupy nad Vltavou, FA in Kraslice, FA Ostrava I, FA Ostrava III, FA , FA in Pilsen, FA Prague 1, FA Prague 4, FA Prague 8, FA in Rakovnék, FA in Sokolov, FA in Tobor, FA in Vysoké Méto, FA in Zlan and FA in Amberk.</seg>
<seg id="103">The Senate of the Czech Court of Auditors approved the audit findings on 27 April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="104">3.2 Examination procedures in Germany</seg>
<seg id="105">The audit area traffic taxes and employees of the assigned PÄB Berlin, Frankfurt/Main and Munich audited from February 2009 to February 2010.</seg>
<seg id="106">After selecting the sample cases, they announced the examination in several countries:</seg>
