<seg id="554">4.5.3 Management of VAT audits for large companies</seg>
<seg id="555">As agreed, neither Court of Auditors examined individual cases. They have examined the question of how the tax administrations proceed in the VAT audit of large companies.</seg>
<seg id="556">Using a questionnaire, they collected information from the tax authorities which is essential for the audit of large enterprises.</seg>
<seg id="557">• What statistical records and evaluations for the VAT audit of large companies are available to the management of the tax administration?</seg>
<seg id="558">Especially:</seg>
<seg id="559">• Are there statistics or records of the extent to which a distinction is made between VAT fraud and general VAT testing?</seg>
<seg id="560">CZ: No, the current version of the ATIS system does not allow such differentiation.</seg>
<seg id="561">Germany: The tax administration makes no distinction between audits to combat VAT fraud and general VAT audits.</seg>
<seg id="562">• Are there statistics or records of the timeliness of the tests?</seg>
<seg id="563">CZ: Information on the timeliness of checks of intra-Community acquisitions of selected VAT payers is recorded in the ATIS system;</seg>
<seg id="564">the same applies to information on the start and end of the IA's audit.</seg>
<seg id="565">Germany: No, the statistics for auditors aggregated at federal level contain only information on the so-called average last audit period (year).</seg>
<seg id="566">This figure does not provide an overview of the audit periods selected for individual companies.</seg>
<seg id="567">USt special auditors focus on the last VAT assessment periods and are also authorised to audit large companies.</seg>
<seg id="568">The statistics for special auditors kept at the federal level do not contain any information on the size class of the audited establishment.</seg>
<seg id="569">• Are there statistics or records of the nature of the additional result; e.g. subdivided by:</seg>
<seg id="570">i. genuine additional result (e.g. application of a reduced rate instead of the general VAT rate)</seg>
<seg id="571">ii. false additional result (e.g. transfer/postponement of a situation which cannot be criticised under VAT law to another tax period)</seg>
<seg id="572">iii. Cash effectiveness (payment of the fixed additional result)</seg>
<seg id="573">Cz:</seg>
<seg id="574">The Czech tax administration monitors the number of tax audits carried out, the amount of the additional tax result, broken down by tax type, the number of taxable persons audited and the number of tax periods audited.</seg>
<seg id="575">Other tax procedures (on-site investigations, dunning procedures) are monitored in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="576">Irrespective of this, the amount of additional payments and the incoming payments are recorded.</seg>
<seg id="577">Statistics on tax liabilities are broken down by tax type. However, no distinction is made between tax liabilities arising from a tax return and those arising from the IA's audit actions.</seg>
<seg id="578">Germany: No, the statistics for auditors and SPECIAL auditors summarised at federal level do not differ according to the above criteria.</seg>
<seg id="579">Most of the tax authorities where local surveys were carried out also did not differentiate in this respect.</seg>
<seg id="580">• Are results-rich test fields recorded?</seg>
<seg id="581">CZ: Yes, the IA can select audit cases based on criteria linked to selected indicators stored in the ATIS system.</seg>
<seg id="582">Germany: There are no regulations at the federal level.</seg>
<seg id="583">Accordingly, the statistics compiled at the federal level for auditors and SPECIAL auditors do not provide such information.</seg>
<seg id="584">However, the federal and state finance ministries have agreed on a common approach.</seg>
<seg id="585">Accordingly, auditors and tax investigators of the Länder are to enter the additional tax result they have achieved in ZAUBER if a certain threshold is exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="586">In this case, additional information shall be provided, e.g. on the origin of the VAT result obtained.</seg>
<seg id="587">• What are the most common findings?</seg>
<seg id="588">Cz:</seg>
<seg id="589">- large taxable companies have unjustifiably benefited from deduction of input tax on supplies and supplies purchased,</seg>
<seg id="590">• not used for an entrepreneurial activity in accordance with Section 72 (1) CZ UStG;</seg>
<seg id="591">• used for representation expenses in accordance with Section 75 (3) CZ UStG;</seg>
<seg id="592">• due to invoices that do not meet the requirements of Section 73 (1) CZ UStG</seg>
<seg id="593">- large taxable holdings have refrained from registering the VAT to be paid in Section 21 (1) of the CZ UStG.</seg>
<seg id="594">Germany: There are no regulations at the federal level.</seg>
<seg id="595">Accordingly, the statistics compiled at the federal level for auditors and SPECIAL auditors do not provide such information.</seg>
<seg id="596">Findings on VAT from audits of large companies are not recorded separately by the countries.</seg>
<seg id="597">However, the Federal Central Tax Office can evaluate the ZAUBER database in which auditors and tax investigators of the Länder are to enter the additional tax result they have achieved if a certain threshold is exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="598">• Does the tax administration analyse audit fields that are rich in results and draw conclusions for strategic management?</seg>
<seg id="599">CZ: Yes, for example, national audits are carried out with regard to high-risk goods and sectors.</seg>
<seg id="600">Germany: There are no regulations at the federal level.</seg>
<seg id="601">Accordingly, the statistics compiled at the federal level for auditors and SPECIAL auditors do not provide information on particularly "productive" audit fields.</seg>
<seg id="602">There were differing views on the analysis of such information, the usefulness and manner in which it was continued to be used.</seg>
<seg id="603">Some senior financial directorates make such information available to the FA, but it is up to the FA whether or not to use it.</seg>
<seg id="604">4.5.4 Comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="605">As a result, large amounts of information are processed automatically in the CZ. Among other things, data from VAT audits as well as key figures from balance sheets, profit and loss accounts are processed in the system.</seg>
<seg id="606">The CZ is able to control the selection of risky cases on the basis of a wide range of information.</seg>
<seg id="607">The same applies to the evaluation and management of VAT audits in general.</seg>
<seg id="608">In the CZ, the establishment of a special tax office for large enterprises is planned for 2012.</seg>
<seg id="609">In Germany, the tax administration does not collect comparable amounts of data.</seg>
<seg id="610">Accordingly, it is more difficult to carry out these tasks in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="611">The emphasis is more on the selection of relevant individual cases.</seg>
<seg id="612">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFBlank</seg>
<seg id="613">On the basis of the information in VAT pre-notifications or VAT declarations as well as inspection instructions, qualified auditors select the cases to be examined and ensure the correct taxation.</seg>
<seg id="614">Appropriate management processes and risk management systems should be put in place to reduce VAT revenue losses while increasing the risk of being discovered for unreliable entrepreneurs.</seg>
<seg id="615">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFBlank</seg>
<seg id="616">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFBlank</seg>
<seg id="617">5. Conclusions</seg>
<seg id="618">The cooperation between the two Courts of Auditors has proved its worth.</seg>
<seg id="619">This has enabled the necessary knowledge to be gained on the systems used in both countries: in particular: • intra-Community turnover, • risk management at the VAT, in particular with regard to the selection of risky transactions, • recovery of VAT claims and • VAT audit of large enterprises.</seg>
<seg id="620">The audit revealed differences in VAT fraud detection strategies and in the systems discussed above.</seg>
<seg id="621">These findings can be used to improve existing procedures.</seg>
<seg id="622">They can also be used to initiate a discussion among interested parties as to which audit approaches and anti-fraud strategies can be used. This applies, for example, to the relationship within and between the Member States and to the EU Commission.</seg>
<seg id="623">The lessons learned and lessons should be encouraged to continue to examine the administration of the VAT together.</seg>
<seg id="624">6th communiqué</seg>
<seg id="625">The report was drawn up in Czech, English and German and signed by the Presidents of the Czech Court of Auditors and the Federal Audit Office.</seg>
<seg id="626">Status of information: June 2010.</seg>
